{"ev": "seen", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "story": {"id": "st-93753101b8ae", "date": "2026-07-21", "stream": "news", "headline": "US strikes Iran for 10th consecutive night as tankers burn in Strait of Hormuz", "summary": "CENTCOM struck Iranian sites for a 10th consecutive night early Tuesday; Iran retaliated against US Gulf assets and hit Bahrain and Kuwait as fires broke out on two tankers in the Strait of Hormuz.", "url": "https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/7/21/hormuz-tankers-on-fire-as-us-iran-continue-attacks-whats-the-latest", "source_domain": "aljazeera.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["geopolitics"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "US Central Command said it completed another round of strikes at 01:00 GMT Tuesday, hitting Iranian military sites on and around Qeshm Island, Bandar Abbas and Bushehr; Iran retaliated against US assets in the Gulf and attacked Bahrain and Kuwait. The White House told Al Jazeera the US would continue strikes unless Trump decides otherwise. The current campaign resumed in early July after the 60-day de-escalation roadmap brokered at Switzerland's Buergenstock resort in June collapsed.", "why": "The Strait of Hormuz carries roughly a fifth of the world's seaborne oil, so tanker fires in the channel put a direct escalation risk on global energy supply and prices, a Swiss household's heating and fuel costs included.", "thread_id": "2026-06-20-cyber-papers-iran-closes-strait-of-hormuz-again-over-israeli", "first_seen_date": "2026-06-20", "event_date": "2026-07-21", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Iran", "United States", "Strait of Hormuz", "CENTCOM"], "status": "settled", "first_seen": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "updated": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "legacy_ids": ["2026-07-21-news-us-strikes-iran-for-10th-consecutive-night-as-ta"], "editions": ["2026-07-21-news"], "origin": "writer:news", "streams": ["news"]}}
{"ev": "publish", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "id": "st-93753101b8ae", "edition": "2026-07-21-news", "fields": {"display_body": "US Central Command said it completed another round of strikes at 01:00 GMT Tuesday, hitting Iranian military sites on and around Qeshm Island, Bandar Abbas and Bushehr; Iran retaliated against US assets in the Gulf and attacked Bahrain and Kuwait. The White House told Al Jazeera the US would continue strikes unless Trump decides otherwise. The current campaign resumed in early July after the 60-day de-escalation roadmap brokered at Switzerland's Buergenstock resort in June collapsed.", "why": "The Strait of Hormuz carries roughly a fifth of the world's seaborne oil, so tanker fires in the channel put a direct escalation risk on global energy supply and prices, a Swiss household's heating and fuel costs included.", "importance": 3, "status": "settled"}}
{"ev": "seen", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "story": {"id": "st-b7bcf923413c", "date": "2026-07-21", "stream": "news", "headline": "Trump to impose 50% tariff on most Canadian goods", "summary": "The White House announced 50% tariffs on most Canadian goods in retaliation for Canada's counter-tariffs on earlier US duties, excluding energy, fish, critical minerals, potash and USMCA-covered goods.", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2026/jul/20/trump-canada-tariffs", "source_domain": "theguardian.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["economy", "geopolitics"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "The measure hits a wide range of products, the White House named wine, hockey sticks and cement, while excluding energy, fish, critical minerals, potash, and goods already covered under the USMCA trade pact or national-security tariffs. Washington accused Canada of unfairly discriminating against American cars, alcohol and dairy; Ottawa says Trump's earlier tariffs breached the trade pact and have raised costs for US families.", "why": "A 50% wall against the US's second-largest trading partner sharply escalates a G7 trade war and threatens supply chains and prices on both sides of the border.", "thread_id": "2026-07-21-news-trump-to-impose-50-tariff-on-most-canadian-goods", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-21", "event_date": "2026-07-20", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["United States", "Canada", "Donald Trump", "USMCA"], "status": "settled", "first_seen": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "updated": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "legacy_ids": ["2026-07-21-news-trump-to-impose-50-tariff-on-most-canadian-goods"], "editions": ["2026-07-21-news"], "origin": "writer:news", "streams": ["news"]}}
{"ev": "publish", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "id": "st-b7bcf923413c", "edition": "2026-07-21-news", "fields": {"display_body": "The measure hits a wide range of products, the White House named wine, hockey sticks and cement, while excluding energy, fish, critical minerals, potash, and goods already covered under the USMCA trade pact or national-security tariffs. Washington accused Canada of unfairly discriminating against American cars, alcohol and dairy; Ottawa says Trump's earlier tariffs breached the trade pact and have raised costs for US families.", "why": "A 50% wall against the US's second-largest trading partner sharply escalates a G7 trade war and threatens supply chains and prices on both sides of the border.", "importance": 2, "status": "settled"}}
{"ev": "seen", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "story": {"id": "st-9576a6d026d3", "date": "2026-07-21", "stream": "news", "headline": "Andy Burnham holds first cabinet, cuts VAT on electricity as UK PM", "summary": "New UK PM Andy Burnham held his first cabinet Tuesday and moved to cut VAT on electricity bills, a day after taking office; he appointed John Healey as chancellor, lifting defence stocks.", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2026/jul/21/world-leaders-congratulate-andy-burnham-becomes-britain-pm", "source_domain": "theguardian.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["politics"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Burnham, who entered Downing Street on 20 July as Britain's seventh prime minister in a decade, succeeding Keir Starmer, appointed John Healey as chancellor; the choice, announced after markets closed Monday, lifted defence stocks on expectations of higher military spending, with Babcock up 7%, BAE Systems up 3% and Rolls-Royce nearly 2%. Macron and Merz were among leaders who called to congratulate him, Merz discussing continued support for Ukraine.", "why": "", "thread_id": "2026-06-22-cyber-papers-keir-starmer-resigns-as-uk-prime-minister-openin", "first_seen_date": "2026-06-22", "event_date": "2026-07-21", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Andy Burnham", "United Kingdom", "John Healey"], "status": "settled", "first_seen": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "updated": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "legacy_ids": ["2026-07-21-news-andy-burnham-holds-first-cabinet-cuts-vat-on-ele"], "editions": ["2026-07-21-news"], "origin": "writer:news", "streams": ["news"]}}
{"ev": "publish", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "id": "st-9576a6d026d3", "edition": "2026-07-21-news", "fields": {"display_body": "Burnham, who entered Downing Street on 20 July as Britain's seventh prime minister in a decade, succeeding Keir Starmer, appointed John Healey as chancellor; the choice, announced after markets closed Monday, lifted defence stocks on expectations of higher military spending, with Babcock up 7%, BAE Systems up 3% and Rolls-Royce nearly 2%. Macron and Merz were among leaders who called to congratulate him, Merz discussing continued support for Ukraine.", "why": "", "importance": 2, "status": "settled"}}
{"ev": "seen", "ts": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "actor": "news", "story": {"id": "st-f0ae684419ed", "date": "2026-07-21", "stream": "news", "headline": "Nicaragua's Ortega says country will hold no more elections", "summary": "Daniel Ortega announced Sunday that Nicaragua will hold no further elections, a step his government says will prevent the opposition from taking power.", "url": "https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jul/20/nicaraguas-president-says-country-will-not-hold-any-more-elections", "source_domain": "theguardian.com", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["politics", "world"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Ortega, the 80-year-old authoritarian leader, made the announcement at the official ceremony marking the 47th anniversary of the 1979 Sandinista revolution.", "why": "Openly ending elections formalises one-party rule in a Central American state that has already jailed or exiled most of its opposition, and deepens Nicaragua's break with the region's democracies.", "thread_id": "2026-07-21-news-nicaragua-s-ortega-says-country-will-hold-no-mor", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-21", "event_date": "2026-07-19", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Nicaragua", "Daniel Ortega"], "status": "settled", "first_seen": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "updated": "2026-07-21T10:11:57Z", "legacy_ids": ["2026-07-21-news-nicaragua-s-ortega-says-country-will-hold-no-mor"], "editions": ["2026-07-21-news"], "origin": "writer:news", "streams": ["news"]}}
